library(dplyr)
library(lubridate)
library(ggplot2)
library(prophet)

Background

In this exercise we will create a time series model using a sales dataset provided in Kaggle. The dataset you will be using is stored under data_input/dive-deeper folder in a file called train.csv. This dataset consist of 4 years of store-item sales data. Along this dive deeper exercise we will perform a time series analysis and forecasting using Prophet model.

Data Preparation

In this section we will prepare our raw dataset into a proper time series format. Please read in our train.csv dataset using read.csv() function we have learned and perform a simple inspection of the data:

sales <- read.csv("data_input/dive-deeper/train.csv")

There are 4 columns observations and variables, consist of information such as date, store number, item number, and item’s sales. Data contains 730,500 rows. It has two varieties of type, date has character type, meanwhile store, item, and sales has integer data type.

After import and understanding data, arrange it sale based on date.

sales_2 <- sales %>% 
  mutate(date = ymd(date)) %>%
  arrange(date)

Then doing data aggregation in dataset from store and item sales. In data above shown column date and total demand based on each transactions.

daily_demand <- sales_2 %>% 
  group_by(date) %>% 
  summarise( 
    demand = sum(sales) 
  )

Visual Exploratory Analysis

Data preparation was completed. Then, we make visualization to understand easily the insight of data than tabular data. X axis explains date and y axis is demand for items.

daily_demand %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=date, y=demand)) + 
  geom_line(color = "tomato3", group=1) + 
  labs( 
    title = "Sales Item Report", 
    subtitle = "all store", 
    caption = "2013-2016",

    y = "Total Sales" 
  ) + 
  theme_minimal()

Data visualization has been created. First, Based on its visualization, we understand and know insight easily. Total sales increase from 2013 until 2016. Second, we have pattern in our total sales, same each year with best sales in middle of year.

Baseline Prophet Model

We are not yet satisfied with visualization in current condition. What we need is prediction for next performance total sales, because it is our goals. So, what we need next is make simple prophet model. Prohet has it rules to fit our data set in its package. Rename date and demand into ds and y.

train_sales <- daily_demand %>%
  rename(
    ds = "date",
    y = "demand"
  )
glimpse(train_sales)
## Rows: 1,461
## Columns: 2
## $ ds <date> 2013-01-01, 2013-01-02, 2013-01-03, 2013-01-04, 2013-01-05, 201...
## $ y  <int> 13696, 13678, 14488, 15677, 16237, 17291, 11769, 13560, 13878, 1...

Then, make our dataset fit with prophet, adjust how many prediction we need. Let’s try for 1 year, because our dataset has frequency in day, so convert 1 year to 365 days. After that, make plot to visualize prediction.

model_sales <- prophet() %>%
  fit.prophet(train_sales)
range(train_sales$ds)
## [1] "2013-01-01" "2016-12-31"
future_365 <- make_future_dataframe(model_sales, periods = 365, freq = "day")
glimpse(future_365)
## Rows: 1,826
## Columns: 1
## $ ds <dttm> 2013-01-01, 2013-01-02, 2013-01-03, 2013-01-04, 2013-01-05, 201...
forecast_365 <- predict(model_sales, future_365)
plot(model_sales, forecast_365)

prophet_plot_components(model_sales, forecast_365)

First information, we get summary with our prediction model. The black dots or points in the graph shows actual time series, and the blue line shows the fitted time series value forecasted 365 days later in the future.Second, there are time series components inform about 3 types condition : trend, weekly seasonality, and yearly seasonality. It useful to know data better and deeper based on time. Data show us, it has uptrend start in 2014. It is different with before that year, which has low sales. Weekly seasonality in this data has grown up start on Thursday until Sunday, meanwhile Monday is lowest sales. Yearly seasonality highes on around August. It has lowest in new year.

Model Fine Tuning

This step to customize model as we want. Add more conditions, like holiday, changepoint, and seasonality. First model above is default from Prophet, some case not fit with real condition, so we need to remodel it with model tuning. Let see how sales data performance through trend line Y = mx + c.

daily_demand %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=date, y=demand)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm")

Trend sales has uptrend or increase each year.

plot(model_sales, forecast_365) +
  add_changepoints_to_plot(model_sales)

Graph above show how prophet tell us about changepoint happen in our data. Some points makes significant different values than regular condition.

before_2014 <- daily_demand %>%
  mutate(
    year=year(date)
  ) %>%
  filter(year < 2014) %>%
  rename(
    ds = "date",
    y = "demand"
  )

after_2014 <- daily_demand %>%
  mutate(
    year = year(date)
  ) %>%
  filter(year >= 2014) %>%
  rename(
    ds = "date",
    y = "demand"
  )

ggplot(before_2014, aes(x=ds, y=y)) +
  geom_point()

ggplot(after_2014, aes(x=ds, y=y)) +
  geom_point()

Seperated data into two dataframe. First is before 2014 and second one is after 2014. Before 2014, especially sales 2013 shows different pattern than the another years.

model_before_2014 <- prophet(yearly.seasonality = TRUE,
                             changepoints = ymd(c("2013-01-01")),
                             changepoint.prior.scale = 0.5) %>%
  fit.prophet(before_2014)
future_before_2014 <- make_future_dataframe(model_before_2014, periods = 365)
forecast_before_2014 <- predict(model_before_2014, future_before_2014)
plot(model_before_2014, forecast_before_2014) +
  add_changepoints_to_plot(model_before_2014) +
  geom_point(data = after_2014, aes(x=as.POSIXct(ds), y=y), color="tomato3")

Try to model with data before and after 2014. We can see it above the graph shows us the visualization insight.

model_6_monthly <- prophet(changepoint.prior.scale = 0.5, yearly.seasonality = FALSE ) %>%
  add_seasonality(name = "monthly", period = 30.5, fourier.order = 5) %>% 
  fit.prophet(train_sales) 
future_6_monthly <- make_future_dataframe(model_6_monthly, periods = 365) 
forecast_6_monthly <- predict(model_6_monthly, future_6_monthly) 
prophet_plot_components(model_6_monthly, forecast_6_monthly)

Turn off for yearly seasonality and try monthly seasonality. In start of month sales seems higher than other date in one month.

plot(model_6_monthly, forecast_6_monthly)

This is visualization of month seasonality of this data.

daily_demand %>%

In this holiday, I choose middle year and new year, which has higher values than other events.

model_holiday <- prophet(changepoint.prior.scale = 0.05,
                         holidays = holiday) %>%
  add_seasonality(name="monthly", period = 30.5, fourier.order = 5) %>%
  fit.prophet(train_sales)
future_holiday <- make_future_dataframe(model_holiday, periods = 365)
forecast_holiday <- predict(model_holiday, future_holiday)
plot(model_holiday, forecast_holiday)

prophet_plot_components(model_holiday, forecast_holiday)

Try various turning, then we can see trend, holiday, weekly, monthly, and yearly.

We score our model with MAPE, to know how many percent this model has risk, before we give it to stakeholder or business.

mape <- function(y, yhat) {
  return(mean(abs(y - yhat)/ y))
}
mape(eval$y, eval$yhat)
## [1] 0.05537844

So, this model has around 6% MAPE. Real condition can be upper or lower than our prediction.

eval %>%
  mutate(
    month=month(ds, label = T)
  ) %>%
  group_by(month) %>%
  summarise(
    mape = mean(abs(y-yhat)/y)
  ) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=month, y=mape)) +
  geom_line(group=1) +
  geom_point() +
  theme_minimal()

This graph shows how MAPE per month. Best result on May until September, but has high risk on December and January. This evaluation can improve this model better with optimization in higher percent.

model_interval <- prophet(changepoint.prior.scale = 0.05,
                          yearly.seasonality = TRUE,
                          holidays = holiday,
                          interval.width = 0.95) %>%
  add_seasonality(name = "monthly", period = 30.5, fourier.order = 5) %>%
  fit.prophet(train)
future_interval <- make_future_dataframe(model_interval, periods = nrow(test)+1)
forecast_interval <- predict(model_interval, future_interval)
plot(model_interval, forecast_interval)

eval %>% 
  mutate( 
    flag_extreme = ifelse(y > yhat_upper | y < yhat_lower, "1", "0"), 
    month = month(ds, label = T), 
  ) %>% 
ggplot(aes(x=ds, y=y)) + 
  geom_ribbon(aes(ymin=yhat_lower, ymax=yhat_upper), alpha = 0.3, fill="dodgerblue4") + 
  geom_line(aes(x=ds, y=yhat)) + 
  geom_point(aes(color=flag_extreme), alpha = 0.5, size = 2) + 
  facet_wrap(~month, scales = "free_x")
